<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Move Thing Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Relocates another Event Point to this Event Point's position, commonly to randomise spawn points, patrol destinations, or objective locations.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Move Thing Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Move Thing</Bold> Event Point moves a target Event Point to the Move Thing Event
        Point's own world position. The target is chosen by Event Point index. When the Move Thing
        fires, the referenced Event Point is relocated to this point's X, Y, and Z coordinates.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Existing missions mostly use Move Thing as a random destination system. Several Move Thing
        Event Points can all target the same Event Point, with each Move Thing placed at a different
        possible location. The mission can then randomly choose one of those locations and move the
        target there.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Move Thing does not move itself. It moves the target Event Point named in Target Waypoint to the Move Thing point's position.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Move Thing uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Letter group and colour are especially
        useful for Move Thing groups, because several Move Thing points often belong to one
        randomisation set.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position is the destination. When the Event Point fires, the target Event Point is moved to
        this Move Thing point's X, Y, and Z coordinates. This means the Move Thing point should be
        placed exactly where the target should end up.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Y Altitude
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Y altitude is part of the destination. Retail examples move targets to different heights,
        including ground level and elevated positions. If the moved target appears underground,
        floating, or unreachable, check the Move Thing point's Y value first.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide when the relocation happens. <Bold>Random</Bold> is the common
        pattern for selecting from multiple possible destinations. <Bold>Dependency</Bold> is useful
        when another mission event should explicitly move the target to this destination.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Move Thing-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Move Thing has one type-specific setting. <Bold>Data[0]</Bold> stores the target Event Point
        index to move.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Target Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Target Waypoint is the Event Point index that will be moved to this Move Thing point's
        position. The editor clamps this value to the valid Event Point range.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Create or identify the target Event Point first, then create each Move Thing destination and set Target Waypoint to that target's index.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Move Thing
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Move Thing usage is heavily focused on random placement. Useful trigger patterns
        are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Random</Bold> - use when one of several Move Thing destinations should be selected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - use when another Event Point should move the target to this specific location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - the observed listening mode for Move Thing entries; use it for normal relocation when the trigger fires.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical setup detail:</Run>
                <Run> Target Waypoint and trigger EP Ref are not always the same thing. Target Waypoint is the Event Point being moved. Trigger EP Ref belongs to the trigger condition.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Move Thing Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Random Spawn Or Objective Location</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use multiple Move Thing Event Points with the same <Bold>Target Waypoint</Bold> when the
        mission needs to move one target to one of several possible locations.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Move Thing <Bold>121</Bold> and Move Thing
        <Bold>122</Bold> both move Event Point <Bold>117</Bold>. Each Move Thing point has a
        different position and uses the <Bold>Random</Bold> trigger with <Bold>Active</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create the Event Point that should be relocated. Add several Move Thing Event Points at the
        possible destinations, set each one's <Bold>Target Waypoint</Bold> to the same target, and
        use the <Bold>Random</Bold> trigger so the mission can choose a destination.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Random Combat Placement</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Move Thing is useful for varying combat setups. It can move patrol points, enemy-related
        positions, or objective markers so repeated plays do not use the exact same location.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>fight1.ucm</Bold>, Move Thing <Bold>6</Bold> and Move Thing <Bold>13</Bold> both
        move Event Point <Bold>4</Bold> to different positions. One destination is at ground level
        and another uses Y altitude <Bold>64</Bold>, showing that height is part of the selected
        destination.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place each Move Thing destination where the target is safe and reachable. Check surrounding
        geometry, roofs, walkables, and altitude before relying on the random setup in a mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Random High/Low Destination</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use Y altitude deliberately when random destinations can be on different floors or height
        levels. This is useful for vertical mission layouts, but it also makes mistakes easier to
        miss.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>FreeCD1.ucm</Bold>, Move Thing <Bold>36</Bold> moves Event Point <Bold>6</Bold>
        to a destination at Y <Bold>1024</Bold>, while Move Thing <Bold>128</Bold> moves the same
        Event Point to a destination at Y <Bold>1408</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Dependency-Controlled Relocation</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when a specific mission event should move the target to a
        specific destination rather than choosing randomly.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>police2.ucm</Bold>, Move Thing <Bold>68</Bold> moves Event Point
        <Bold>13</Bold> and uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>24</Bold>. In this
        setup, Event Point <Bold>13</Bold> is the target being moved, while Event Point
        <Bold>24</Bold> is the trigger dependency.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set <Bold>Target Waypoint</Bold> to the Event Point you want to relocate. Then set the
        trigger to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that
        should cause the relocation.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Move Thing Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the Event Point that needs to be moved.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Move Thing</Bold> Event Point at the destination location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Target Waypoint</Bold> to the Event Point index that should move.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set this Move Thing point's X, Y, and Z to the exact destination.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For random placement, create several Move Thing points with the same Target Waypoint and use <Bold>Random</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For scripted relocation, use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set EP Ref to the Event Point that should cause the move.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Keep related Move Thing points in the same colour and letter group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test every possible destination to make sure the moved target is valid, reachable, and not inside geometry.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> Target Waypoint is the Event Point to move, this point's coordinates are the intended destination, the trigger is either Random or a deliberate dependency, and every possible destination has been tested in-game.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
